{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Xb9RYjfKAudMRZdWRW5NNy","type":"tool_result","content":"388:.log-viewer {\n389-    background: var(--bg-surface);\n390-    border: 1px solid var(--border);\n391-    border-radius: var(--radius);\n392-    max-height: 600px;\n393-    overflow: auto;\n394-    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\n395-}\n396-\n397:.log-viewer pre {\n398-    margin: 0;\n399-    padding: 0.75rem;\n400-    font-family: var(--mono);\n401-    font-size: 0.8rem;\n402-    white-space: pre-wrap;\n403-    word-break: break-word;\n404-    line-height: 1.4;\n405-}\n406-\n407-.log-line { display: block; }\n--\n595:    .log-viewer { max-height: 400px; }\n596-    .drawer { width: 100%; right: -100%; }\n597-}"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"b4591c00-1384-4a12-a964-ae35a19bcedb","uuid":"d7243072-2fdf-4127-93c4-4e9615c733cc","tool_use_result":{"mode":"content","numFiles":0,"filenames":[],"content":"388:.log-viewer {\n389-    background: var(--bg-surface);\n390-    border: 1px solid var(--border);\n391-    border-radius: var(--radius);\n392-    max-height: 600px;\n393-    overflow: auto;\n394-    margin-bottom: 1.5rem;\n395-}\n396-\n397:.log-viewer pre {\n398-    margin: 0;\n399-    padding: 0.75rem;\n400-    font-family: var(--mono);\n401-    font-size: 0.8rem;\n402-    white-space: pre-wrap;\n403-    word-break: break-word;\n404-    line-height: 1.4;\n405-}\n406-\n407-.log-line { display: block; }\n--\n595:    .log-viewer { max-height: 400px; }\n596-    .drawer { width: 100%; right: -100%; }\n597-}","numLines":24}}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01HhdjHt6a5fqTSED1GD69ap","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I understand the structure. The scroll position issue likely comes from the fact that when SSE events come in rapidly (especially when streaming a completed run's full log), each `appendLogLine` call does:\n\n1. Creates a `<span>` element\n2. Appends it to `logContent` (the `<pre>` element)\n3. If `autoScroll`, sets `scrollTop` to `scrollHeight`\n\nThe problem is likely a race condition with the scroll event listener. When `autoScroll` is set and the browser auto-scrolls, the scroll event fires, and the check at line 122 may evaluate before the browser has finished updating the layout, causing `autoScroll` to be incorrectly set to `false`.\n \nWait, I need to reconsider what the actual issue is. The user is saying the scroll position resets when new SSE events arrive, and they want it to stay stable so they can keep reading. The code uses `appendChild` which shouldn't reset scroll on its own, but the scroll event handler that fires when `scrollTop` is programmatically set might be triggering the `autoScroll` flag to toggle incorrectly, causing the scroll to jump around.\n\nThe real problem is likely that when new content arrives and gets appended, if `autoScroll` is true, the code forces a scroll to the bottom with `logViewer.scrollTop = logViewer.scrollHeight`. But if the user has manually scrolled up to read earlier logs, they get yanked back down before they can even turn off `autoScroll` through the scroll event listener. So the scroll position isn't stable—it keeps getting pulled to the bottom as new lines arrive. I'm wondering if the real culprit is the `location.reload()` call when the run state changes, which would reset scroll position entirely. The SSE log events themselves shouldn't cause this, but if the polling detects a state change and triggers a reload, that would explain the unexpected scroll reset the user is experiencing. I think the real problem is that when SSE delivers a burst of messages—especially from `streamFullLog` sending all lines at once—`appendLogLine` gets called repeatedly in quick succession, and each call triggers an auto-scroll that keeps pulling the user back down even if they're trying to scroll up. The fix would be to batch scroll updates using `requestAnimationFrame`, distinguish between user-initiated and programmatic scrolling so `autoScroll` only changes based on actual user interaction, and stabilize the scroll position before making DOM changes.\n\nActually, a simpler approach might work better: check if the user is at the bottom before appending content, append the new lines, then only scroll to the new bottom if they were already there—otherwise leave their scroll position alone since the browser naturally preserves it when content is added below. The current code probably tries to do this, but there's likely a race condition or timing issue causing the unwanted scroll behavior. I'm setting up a more robust version that tracks scroll state and prevents the scroll event listener from interfering with programmatic scrolls.\n\nWriting scroll detection logic... I'm realizing the synchronous flag approach won't work reliably since scroll events can fire at unpredictable times depending on the browser. Instead, I should use a flag that gets set when we programmatically scroll and then cleared after a brief delay, which gives the scroll event time to fire before we reset it. The real challenge is distinguishing between user scrolls, our auto-scroll updates, and browser adjustments from DOM changes—a common pattern is to set an ignore flag before programmatic scrolls so the handler can skip updating the auto-scroll state on those specific events.\n\nStill writing the scroll handler... I'm reconsidering the approach — scroll events fire synchronously when `scrollTop` changes in modern browsers, but there could be edge cases I'm not accounting for. A simpler strategy would be to track whether the user was at the bottom before appending, then conditionally scroll or preserve the position afterward. I'm setting up a scroll listener that checks if we're near the bottom, and then modifying the append function to respect that state.\n\nWriting the append logic... I'm realizing the scroll position logic needs careful handling—when we programmatically set `scrollTop`, it triggers scroll events that could interfere with the `atBottom` calculation, but the math actually works out because setting `scrollTop = scrollHeight` gets clamped to the maximum scroll position, making the distance-from-bottom check equal zero and keeping `autoScroll` true as intended.\n\nNow I'm wondering if the real issue is something else entirely—maybe the `white-space: pre-wrap` on the `<pre>` element is causing content reflow when long lines are added, and if the scrollbar appears or disappears, that width change could be triggering unexpected behavior.\n\nActually, I think I've found it. When the SSE stream starts, the log viewer is empty, so `scrollHeight` equals `clientHeight`. As lines come in, `autoScroll` keeps us at the bottom, but the server's `streamFullLog` function sends all the log lines in rapid succession, and the client's `onmessage` handler fires repeatedly in quick succession, which might be overwhelming the scroll logic.\n\nThe real issue is that for a large log, hundreds or thousands of `appendLogLine` calls happen back-to-back, each one appending a DOM element and potentially scrolling. This creates jank and, more importantly, if the page loads and immediately gets hit with a burst of log lines, the scroll position is constantly being reset to the bottom, leaving no opportunity for the user to scroll up until everything's processed.\n\nThe task description \"SSE log events reset the scroll position\" suggests that when new lines trickle in during an active run, the scroll jumps unexpectedly, interrupting the user's reading. I need to make the fix robust by batching DOM updates so we're not constantly re-rendering and re-scrolling.\n\nMy approach is to collect incoming lines in a buffer and flush them together using `requestAnimationFrame`, check whether we're at the bottom before the batch, and only auto-scroll after if we were already at the bottom. If the user has scrolled up to read, I'll preserve their scroll position instead of forcing it back down.\n\nImplementing the scroll tracking and batching logic... Still writing the log batching logic...\n\nThe scroll event handler should work correctly as-is since programmatic scrolls will either auto-scroll to the bottom or restore the saved position, and the handler will update the `autoScroll` flag accordingly. I'm also considering the edge case where the user scrolls while lines are queued in the animation frame—in that case, the saved scroll position would be overwritten by their manual scroll, which is the right behavior. event fires and updates `autoScroll`. Then in `flushLogLines`, `wasAtBottom` reads the current value of `autoScroll`, and `savedScrollTop` reads the current scroll position. Wait, no - `flushLogLines` captures `autoScroll` and `logViewer.scrollTop` at the time it runs, which is after the user's scroll. So it would correctly use the new scroll state. Good.\n\nActually wait, there's a subtle issue. `var wasAtBottom = autoScroll;` captures the autoScroll value, but `autoScroll` is set by the scroll event handler which fires on user scroll. If the user scrolls up (setting `autoScroll = false`) and then immediately a log line comes in, `appendLogLine` queues it and requests an animation frame. In the animation frame, `wasAtBottom` is `false` (correct), `savedScrollTop` is the user's scroll position (correct), the DOM updates and scroll gets restored properly.\n\nNow I need to implement this and verify the existing tests still pass, so let me look for the web UI test suite.","signature":"